achment','image/svg+xml',0),(662,2,'2024-11-18 12:39:57','2024-11-18 12:39:57','','video-surveillance','','inherit','open','closed','','video-surveillance','','','2024-11-18 12:39:57','2024-11-18 12:39:57','',627,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/video-surveillance.svg',0,'attachment','image/svg+xml',0),(663,2,'2024-11-18 12:42:34','2024-11-18 12:42:34','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>[bandwidth_calculater]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Bandwidth Calculator','','inherit','closed','closed','','581-autosave-v1','','','2024-11-18 12:42:34','2024-11-18 12:42:34','',581,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/?p=663',0,'revision','',0),(667,14,'2024-11-18 21:17:54','2024-11-18 21:17:54','','Community','','publish','closed','closed','','community-3','','','2024-11-18 21:17:54','2024-11-18 21:17:54','',0,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/?p=667',4,'nav_menu_item','',0),(671,14,'2024-11-19 14:32:51','2024-11-19 14:32:51','<p>Can someone answer this?</p>','','','publish','closed','closed','','671','','','2024-11-19 14:32:51','2024-11-19 14:32:51','',652,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/forums/reply/671/',1,'reply','',0),(672,37,'2024-11-20 15:24:06','2024-11-20 15:24:06','<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Overview</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The storage market is competitively mature from a price and functionality perspective. With marketing programs and product differentiation being the most significant battleground. However, technological developments such as solid state/flash improvements create disruption from a performance and infrastructure perspective. Vendors are challenged to differentiate their products and to position storage offerings to compete with storage cloud subscription costs. Therefore, storage array vendors offer repackaged decades old software defined storage products and subscription pricing models. Nevertheless, many customers still prefer to have in-house data centres for security and cost transparency requirements when cloud infrastructure accountability, legal data protection requirements cannot be assured, and costs expand out of control.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontStyle\":\"normal\",\"fontWeight\":\"300\"}},\"fontSize\":\"medium\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\" style=\"font-style:normal;font-weight:300\">Key Insights</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The storage array market is stable with enterprise customers purchasing approximately $20-$25bn of storage systems/arrays per annum for the past five years.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Solid State Disk is replacing disks (HDD), but the total replacement of HDD by SSD will take more than a decade.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Software Defined Storage is a successful marketing program to re-classify software such as filesystems, provisioning, device management etc as a new technology. However, all storage arrays and servers have always been software defined and determined by the software within the storage arrays.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>The most significant storage challenges are provisioning, capacity expansion and lack of transparency within subscription pricing models.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Storage performance is no longer a significant challenge, data management (archiving, legal data protection requirements) are more challenging, and this is the next big opportunity for storage vendors to innovate.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontStyle\":\"normal\",\"fontWeight\":\"300\"}},\"fontSize\":\"medium\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\" style=\"font-style:normal;font-weight:300\">Suggested guidance for enterprise customers</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>When purchasing storage hardware, request detailed/itemised breakout of all hardware, software, support, maintenance, installation services, training courses, trade-in values, discounts per line items in all storage purchase offers.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>When purchasing software defined storage, do not forget to include the cost of the hardware such as; server storage, virtualization software or dedicated storage server(s). Software defined storage does not work without hardware. And hardware does not work without operating systems and storage software.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Storage arrays purchased with subscription payment methods need to be analysed in detail. For example, will the system being purchased be larger than required. Because it contains large amounts of unused and unpaid storage which requires a large amount of rack or floor space for these unused physical resources.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Invest in vendors that provide solid data management offerings that include data tiering, space reclamation, data classification, ransomware detection and protection.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Analysis</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontStyle\":\"normal\",\"fontWeight\":\"300\"}},\"fontSize\":\"medium\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\" style=\"font-style:normal;font-weight:300\">Storage Technologies</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The density or storage capacity of NAND doubles every two-three year, with the average SSD capacity being 6TB, popular formats being in the 2-16TB range. However, the capacity of HDDs increases by 30% every 2yrs. The most used HDD capacity in enterprise storage is in the 20-32TB range, lower capacities for active data and higher capacities for archival storage. From a technology perspective expect 50TB HDDs in a couple years, but this will be used for storing inactive/archival data. Tape (which is mostly LTO format) increases in capacity by 30%. Common LTO tape capacity sizes today are 30-50TB.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontStyle\":\"normal\",\"fontWeight\":\"300\"}},\"fontSize\":\"medium\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\" style=\"font-style:normal;font-weight:300\">Purchasing/Buying behaviours.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Storage hardware (HDD, NAND, Tape) is still mainly purchased as a one-time capital purchase, as are other base IT datacenter base hardware components such as servers and network switches. However, backup software and storage appliances are purchased on a subscription basis. This is interesting as this buying behaviour has not changed for the past 40yrs. Which indicates that there are sound business reasons for buying hardware outright but software as a subscription.<br>While storage vendors are beginning to offer Storage as a Service that offers a consumption model like ‘pay-as-you-go’ that cloud vendors providers provide, the model has not been successful. In fact enterprise customers will end up paying 30% more over a five year period when compared to traditional one-time capital purchase. Certain verticals such as IT service providers and telecommunication vendors seem to show some interest in this model.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontStyle\":\"normal\",\"fontWeight\":\"300\"}},\"fontSize\":\"medium\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\" style=\"font-style:normal;font-weight:300\">The data conundrum</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Storage is a temporary solution, whereas keeping data is for “life”. The reality is that storage systems are tactical purchases which may be owned and used for 3-7yrs. Whereas, keeping data in true fidelity is a strategic problem or challenge. This results in the IT management or data management challenge of constantly having to migrate old expired or off support storage systems to newer supported storage systems. There may be one exception to this which is tape storage. This is because tape storage has a lifespan of approximately 15yrs, whereas HDD’s have a lifespan of 3-5yrs and SSD’s 5-7yrs. Even though tape storage does reduce storage costs for data management, tape is not “fashionable” and has become a niche. Nevertheless, it is still used for “deep storage” in many archives. This is because tape does not require electricity when it is not being used. However, searching for data within tape systems is slow compared to HDD and SSD. This is due to the sequential access nature of tape media. Nevertheless, indexing systems or virtual tape solutions can enable faster tape search if the data on tape media has been indexed on a faster HDD/SSD system and then the data on a tape can be accessed more quickly by direct access or “fast wind” to the appropriate section of the tape.<br>On-premises object storage system provide an alternative to tape and provide ‘active-archiving’ capabilities that makes data searching and retrieval much quicker than tape. However, object storage on-premises is 10 times the cost of tape.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontStyle\":\"normal\",\"fontWeight\":\"300\"}},\"fontSize\":\"medium\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\" style=\"font-style:normal;font-weight:300\"><br>Green IT/Storage</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It is extremely difficult to obtain a “green” storage infrastructure. Storage devices require special waste disposal techniques and large amounts of reliable electricity. All storage systems require electricity except for inactive HDDs which are powered down/hibernating or inactive tapes. SSDs require less electricity than active HDDs but with the cost of SSDs decreasing and workloads becoming larger more SSDs are used, therefore negating their energy savings.<br>Artificial Intelligence, Machine Learning, Big Data, large search engines, Natural Language Processing, Quantum computing is driving the demand for fast results and fast storage response times (low latency). Simultaneously large storage capacities demand is also increasing. Therefore, the quantity or electricity required increases as does energy/electricity for cooling of storage devices and servers/CPUs.<br>Ultimately, this results in increased energy demands which require reliable, uninterruptible power supplies. Therefore, renewables plus batteries with variable intermittent solar/wind power cannot be used to power large data centres. Batteries cannot store the amount of electricity to power a datacenter when renewables do not work. Therefore recently, SMR (Small Nuclear Reactors) are being proposed to provide reliable, sustainable green electricity. Ultimately due to the physical/electronic nature of computer equipment and storage devices the electrical components cannot be environmentally sustainable without some sort of technological shift into biological storage such as DNA storage, neurons or such like. However, today reliable low-cost biological storage is not available.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontStyle\":\"normal\",\"fontWeight\":\"300\"}},\"fontSize\":\"medium\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\" style=\"font-style:normal;font-weight:300\"><br>Cloud Storage.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To maintain competitiveness, hyperscale cloud vendors are integrating storage components to build their own low cost storage infrastructure. Cloud vendors are very price sensitive due to high price sensitivity and therefore economies of scale are extremely important for cloud vendors to drive down storage costs. However, cloud vendors also have great purchasing power which enables leverage over storage and all other IT component suppliers. Therefore, to drive down storage costs the hyperscale and to some extent smaller cloud vendors have started to create their own storage devices, by building their own storage systems/infrastructures. This is often done by buying the storage media SSD NAND chips and HDDs directly from the component manufacturers. And then integrating these into their own storage systems with servers/motherboards with storage file systems (aka software defined storage) to distribute the data and low cost ethernet connections.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><br>Conclusion</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Purchasing storage is determined by your business, organisational or legal requirements. These high-level requirements reciprocally create applications which require specific response times, availability and performance demands. Therefore, ultimately the cost and type of storage used by applications is determined by response times, bandwidth, throughput, availability and recovery/failover time.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','The Enterprise Storage Market in 2024','','publish','open','closed','','the-enterprise-storage-market-in-2024','','','2024-11-20 15:24:07','2024-11-20 15:24:07','',0,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/?post_type=market_research&#038;p=672',0,'market_research','',0),(673,14,'2024-11-20 15:18:50','2024-11-20 15:18:50','','EnterpriseStorage','','inherit','open','closed','','enterprisestorage','','','2024-11-20 15:18:50','2024-11-20 15:18:50','',672,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/EnterpriseStorage.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(675,22,'2024-11-20 20:51:23','2024-11-20 20:51:23','<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Overview</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontStyle\":\"normal\",\"fontWeight\":\"300\"}},\"fontSize\":\"medium\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\" style=\"font-style:normal;font-weight:300\">Key Insights</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>TCO Reduction</strong>: All-flash data centres provide up to a 40% lower Total Cost of Ownership (TCO) compared to traditional hard disk systems due to savings in power, space, and operational costs</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Sustainability Advantage</strong>: Flash storage consumes 90% less energy and generates 85% less e-waste than HDD-based systems, making it an environmentally friendly option for enterprises looking to reduce their carbon footprint</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Superior Performance</strong>: Flash arrays deliver up to 10 times the efficiency in terms of energy and space consumption, making them far more scalable and reliable than HDDs</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Cost Competitiveness</strong>: With new QLC NAND technologies, all-flash arrays have become cost-competitive with HDDs for large-scale deployments. The price per gigabyte of flash is rapidly approaching parity with HDDs, especially when considering effective capacity</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Technology Longevity</strong>: As flash technology progresses, the density of storage per drive is expected to skyrocket, with predictions of 200TB drives by 2026, further solidifying the longevity and feasibility of all-flash systems for future data centre growth.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Analysis</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontStyle\":\"normal\",\"fontWeight\":\"300\"}},\"fontSize\":\"medium\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\" style=\"font-style:normal;font-weight:300\">Economic Feasibility of All-Flash Data Centres</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The economic feasibility of all-flash data centres has shifted dramatically over the past few years, largely due to advances in flash and memory technology and the ability to deliver cost-competitive solutions at scale. The adoption of flash storage can reduce energy consumption by up to 90%, drastically cutting power costs in data centres.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While traditional HDDs were once the go-to option for enterprises looking for a low-cost solution, the operational inefficiencies and frequent hardware refreshes associated with mechanical storage add up. This has resulted in an overall decline in sales of traditional HDD. Figure 1 shows the decline in unit shipments in the las ten years. From an all-time peak of 651 million units shipped in 2010, shipments have fallen almost 71% to 166 million in 2022.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":676,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/HDD-shipments.jpg\" alt=\"Figure 1 - HDD shipments\" class=\"wp-image-676\" title=\"Figure 1 - HDD shipments\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Figure 1 - HDD shipments</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Flash media cost per gigabyte has been declining at roughly 20% per year, while HDD cost per gigabyte has been dropping at only 9% per year. Moreover, with companies now offering flash solutions at under $0.20 per GB with support included, the financial argument for sticking with HDDs becomes less compelling. Enterprises that once saw flash as too expensive are now finding it a viable option, especially given the cost savings related to reduced physical space, cooling, and administrative overhead.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontStyle\":\"normal\",\"fontWeight\":\"300\"}},\"fontSize\":\"medium\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\" style=\"font-style:normal;font-weight:300\">Performance and Scalability in Modern Data Centres</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Flash arrays are unrivalled when it comes to performance. Unlike HDDs, which are constrained by physical read/write heads, flash modules can perform multiple simultaneous operations without degradation in performance. Today, most flash systems offer up to 10 times the efficiency of HDDs in terms of IOPS, space, and energy consumption.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Additionally, flash modules offer far quicker rebuild times and dramatically lower failure rates compared to HDDs, which face increased risk of data loss as capacities grow. This makes flash a far more reliable and scalable solution for enterprises that need to handle growing data volumes efficiently.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Performance is one of the most significant differentiators between flash and HDD systems. While HDDs struggle with limitations such as read/write heads and rotational latency, flash modules are inherently faster due to their lack of moving parts. This results in flash storage delivering thousands of times the Input/Output Operations Per Second (IOPS) compared to HDDs.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For modern enterprises running data-intensive applications, such as big data analytics or artificial intelligence workloads, this performance leap is crucial. Flash arrays can handle significantly higher volumes of simultaneous requests without bottlenecks, which is a major advantage over HDDs that struggle under heavy I/O workloads. In addition, flash systems like.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Another key advantage of flash is its scalability. As data growth continues to skyrocket, enterprises are forced to scale their storage infrastructure. HDD-based systems face limitations in scaling due to both physical size and operational inefficiencies. Flash systems, on the other hand, are designed to scale seamlessly.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Additionally, flash storage solutions are not bound by the same rebuild limitations that plague HDDs. In the event of a failure, flash systems can recover data much faster, minimizing downtime and ensuring data integrity is maintained, which is particularly important for mission-critical applications.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontStyle\":\"normal\",\"fontWeight\":\"300\"}},\"fontSize\":\"medium\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\" style=\"font-style:normal;font-weight:300\">Environmental Impact and Sustainability</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The sustainability benefits of flash-based storage cannot be overstated. With data centres responsible for approximately 1% of global energy consumption, enterprises are under increasing pressure to reduce their environmental impact. Flash storage solutions are inherently more energy-efficient, consuming up to 90% less power than their HDD counterparts. For example, compared to a 7.2K RPM SATA disk, an SSD consumes one-ninth of the power per byte stored1. Figure 2 shows the power consumption in Watts per TB for various drive types. Traditional HDDs consume up to 6x more power compared to flash modules of equivalent capacity, while also requiring more cooling due to their mechanical operations.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For enterprises with vast amounts of data, the ability to save not only on energy but also on cooling can significantly impact their operational budgets. A comparison between HDD and flash-based systems shows that flash can save up to 60% in operational costs over a six-year period.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This reduction in energy consumption not only contributes to a lower carbon footprint but also translates to substantial financial savings for organizations. Flash systems have been shown to generate up to 85% less e-waste due to their longer lifespan and lack of moving parts. This is particularly critical as the global focus shifts toward more sustainable practices in IT infrastructure.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Moreover, flash storage’s compact nature further enhances its sustainability profile. By reducing the physical footprint of data centers, enterprises can significantly decrease the materials used in construction and the resources required for maintenance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":677,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/PowerConsumptionofVariousDriveTypes-1024x615.jpg\" alt=\"Figure 2 Power consumption of various drive types\" class=\"wp-image-677\" title=\"Power consumption of various drive types\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Figure 2 Power consumption of various drive types</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Traditional HDD-based systems require large amounts of space, often demanding expansive data center environments, which contribute to higher energy usage for both operation and cooling. In contrast, flash arrays can deliver more capacity in a fraction of the physical space, making them ideal for organizations looking to minimize their environmental impact without sacrificing storage performance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Furthermore, in SSDs, when comparing quad-level cell (QLC) flash to triple-level cell (TLC) flash, both generate similar levels of heat, resulting in comparable cooling needs for data centers. However, QLC flash offers a higher storage density than TLC, allowing data centers to store significantly more data within the same physical footprint. This increased capacity enables better space efficiency, which is critical for data centers looking to optimize their infrastructure without expanding their physical footprint.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As regulatory and environmental pressures continue to mount, flash storage offers a viable path for enterprises to meet sustainability goals while improving operational efficiency.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontStyle\":\"normal\",\"fontWeight\":\"300\"}},\"fontSize\":\"medium\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\" style=\"font-style:normal;font-weight:300\">Visualizing the all flash data centre</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Given the cost economics of all flash and its impact on sustainability, it is now possible for designing an all-flash data centre for primary and secondary storage environments. For example, production grade, mission critical workloads can be deployed on NVMe-oF based storage systems that use TLC or MLC memory technologies. All business-critical workloads that do not require sub-millisecond level response times can leverage QLC based storage systems. Backup systems too can be deployed using QLC media. This significantly accelerates recovery time and is cost efficient. Technologies such as wear-levelling and over provisioning help significantly reduce the failure rate of the drives. Data reduction technologies such as compression, deduplication and compaction deliver at least 3:1 data reduction capability further reducing storage acquisition costs. Figure 3 shows a view of the all-flash data centre.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":678,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/TheAll-FlashDataCenter-1024x457.png\" alt=\"Figure 3 – The all-flash data center\" class=\"wp-image-678\"/><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\">Figure 3 – The all-flash data center</figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontStyle\":\"normal\",\"fontWeight\":\"300\"}},\"fontSize\":\"medium\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\" style=\"font-style:normal;font-weight:300\">Future Trends and Long-Term Viability</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Looking to the future, flash technology is positioned to dominate the data storage market, as advancements in flash drive capacities continue to accelerate. By 2026, we anticipate delivering flash drives will reach over 200TB capacity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This leap in storage density will further tip the scales in favor of flash-based systems, rendering traditional HDDs obsolete, even in applications where cost per gigabyte has traditionally been the deciding factor. As NAND prices continue to fall and the technology evolves, the price gap between flash and HDDs will likely disappear entirely. This will eliminate the last remaining advantage HDDs have over flash storage, making flash the default choice for enterprises.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Furthermore, the ongoing innovations in flash technology are focused on enhancing not only capacity but also the overall performance and reliability of storage systems. Technologies today allow enterprises to continuously upgrade their storage systems without downtime, keeping pace with the latest advancements without needing to replace entire systems.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This ensures that all-flash data centres will remain relevant for the foreseeable future, offering a future-proof solution for organizations looking to scale their storage infrastructure. As the data centre landscape continues to evolve, flash storage is poised to meet the demands of modern enterprises, delivering the performance, scalability, and sustainability required in a digital-first world.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Conclusion</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The all-flash data centre is no longer a distant future vision; it is a present-day reality driven by economic, performance, and sustainability advantages. The decline in NAND costs and advances in flash\\ technologies have made flash storage a cost-competitive option for enterprises of all sizes, while also delivering superior performance, scalability, and reliability compared to traditional HDD-based systems. Flash arrays provide enterprises with the ability to significantly reduce their TCO while also minimizing their environmental footprint.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With data consumption set to grow exponentially in the coming years, the need for scalable, efficient, and sustainable storage solutions is more pressing than ever. HDDs, once seen as the go-to for capacity-driven workloads, are now being outpaced by the advancements in flash technology. Flash systems not only address current data center challenges but also offer a clear path forward as enterprises strive for greater efficiency and sustainability. By 2026, the storage market will likely see the complete obsolescence of HDDs in favour of all-flash architectures, marking the beginning of a new era in data centre design and operation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>References</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>https://www.energy.gov/sites/prod/files/2015/01/f19/UMPChapter20-data-center-IT.pdf</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','Should you move to an All-Flash Data centre?','','publish','open','closed','','should-you-move-to-an-all-flash-data-centre','','','2024-12-31 06:06:22','2024-12-31 06:06:22','',0,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/?post_type=market_research&#038;p=675',0,'market_research','',0),(676,14,'2024-11-20 20:35:12','2024-11-20 20:35:12','','HDD shipments','','inherit','open','closed','','hdd-shipments','','','2024-11-20 20:35:12','2024-11-20 20:35:12','',675,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/HDD-shipments.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(677,14,'2024-11-20 20:42:51','2024-11-20 20:42:51','','PowerConsumptionofVariousDriveTypes','','inherit','open','closed','','powerconsumptionofvariousdrivetypes','','','2024-11-20 20:42:51','2024-11-20 20:42:51','',675,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/PowerConsumptionofVariousDriveTypes.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(678,14,'2024-11-20 20:4