'post','',0),(709,14,'2025-01-05 19:38:13','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Abstract</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As the world becomes more digitally connected, there is a growing demand for efficient and real-time processing of data closer to the source. Edge computing has emerged as a transformative paradigm that brings computation and data storage closer to end-users and devices. This white paper aims to explore the goal of edge computing, identify the challenges associated with its implementation, propose effective methods to deal with these challenges, and conclude with the potential benefits and impact of edge computing on various industries.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Executive Summary</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Edge computing is an emerging paradigm that brings computation and data storage closer to the location where it is needed, to improve response times and save bandwidth. This summary examines the essential elements, challenges, and solutions for effective edge computing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Key elements for edge computing include consistent low latency, resilience to network disruptions, security through zero trust models, any-scale scalability, zero touch provisioning, and a shift from human decisions to automated decisions at the edge. Challenges involve managing heterogeneous infrastructure, resource constraints, data management, security risks, optimizing performance and costs, lack of skilled technicians, and lack of purpose-built solutions. Also current generative AI implementation especially Large Language Models (LLM) fall short of taking a prominent role in Edge computing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Recommended approaches to overcoming these challenges include industry collaboration for standards, edge data caching and prioritization, secure device bootstrapping and over-the-air updates, TinyML for machine learning on small devices, abstraction layers above hardware, and containerization of hardware resources.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The most critical technologies identified are TinyML for local machine learning on small devices, efficient abstraction layers above hardware, and any-scale scalability. Together, these can enable automated low-latency decisions at the edge, application portability across devices, and flexible scaling of edge resources. By combining key technologies like these, edge computing can deliver on its promise of distributed intelligence and transformation across industries.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Introduction</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The digital landscape has witnessed exponential growth in data generation, driven by the proliferation of Internet of Things (IoT) devices, 5G connectivity, and the increasing demand for real-time data processing. Traditional cloud computing models, while powerful, face limitations related to latency, bandwidth, and data privacy. Edge computing presents a compelling solution to address these challenges and create a more responsive and agile ecosystem.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Goal of Edge Computing</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Contrary to traditional notions, edge computing encompasses more than just reducing latency and improving user experience by bringing computational power and data storage closer to the<br>data source or end-users. At its core, edge computing revolves around the concepts of data mastery and data commercialization. Its ultimate aim is to empower organizations with real-time data control, enabling informed decision-making that enhances key performance indicators (KPIs) and optimizes user experiences while remaining cost-effective.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":710,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/goalofEdgeComputing.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-710\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Edge computing recognizes the significance of gaining comprehensive understanding of data assets, effectively managing them, and utilizing them strategically within an organization. This mastery of data allows businesses to unlock valuable insights, make data-driven decisions, and drive operational efficiency. Simultaneously, edge computing acknowledges the commercial potential of data. By transforming data into marketable products, services, or insights, organizations can create new revenue streams and capitalize on their data assets.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Data commercialization</strong> is the process of utilizing a company\'s data to drive business value beyond data monetization. Unlike data monetization which focuses on selling data as a standalone product, data commercialization aims to extract tangible value from data to improve business operations, uncover new opportunities, and create competitive advantages.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Data mastery</strong> refers to the comprehensive understanding and management of data within an organization to derive maximum value. It goes beyond data collection and involves processes to gain deep insight into the meaning, accuracy, and potential use cases of data. It enables optimizing data quality, implementing governance practices, and leveraging technologies like machine learning to uncover patterns and trends. The end goal is to establish authoritative knowledge of the organization\'s data landscape and ability to harness data effectively for strategic goals. It empowers data-driven decision making at all levels for increased operational efficiency, risk mitigation, and innovation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In essence, edge computing surpasses its initial goals and delves into the realms of data mastery and commercialization. It seeks to empower organizations with control over their real-time data, leading to enhanced decision-making, improved KPIs, and optimized user experiences. All of this is accomplished while maintaining a focus on cost-effectiveness and staying at the forefront of technological advancements.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Essentials</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To unlock the true potential of edge computing in the future, there are essential requirements that must be met.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":711,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/EdgeComputing-essential.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-711\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Consistent &amp; Predictable Low Latency</strong>: Consistent and predictable low latency is of utmost importance in edge computing, unlocking its transformative potential. The proliferation of real-time applications necessitates low latency, from autonomous vehicles to industrial automation and augmented/virtual reality. Delays in data processing can lead to critical consequences like safety hazards, production inefficiencies, or degraded user experiences. Consistency and predictability are equally crucial. Reliable response times are essential for uninterrupted user experiences, as inconsistent latency can result in jittery video streams, dropped connections, or data inaccuracies, eroding trust. In conclusion, consistent and predictable low latency in edge computing is indispensable for real-time applications, managing IoT device data, and supporting industries requiring split-second decisions. As edge computing continues to reshape industries, optimizing latency is pivotal for a seamless, efficient, and reliable digital ecosystem.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Resilience To Network Disconnection &amp; Optimized Bandwidth</strong>: maintaining resilience to network disconnection is crucial for uninterrupted device functionality in environments with unreliable connectivity. Local data processing and storage enable autonomous operation, reducing reliance on continuous cloud connectivity. Optimizing bandwidth utilization is equally vital, given the growing data volume from IoT devices and real-time applications. Edge computing filters and analyzes data at the edge, minimizing raw data transmission to the cloud and conserving valuable bandwidth. This combined approach ensures continuous operation, enhances data security, and delivers a responsive ecosystem that meets modern application demands. As edge computing evolves, its ability to adapt to network challenges and optimize resource usage solidifies its position as a cornerstone technology across industries.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Zero Trust Security</strong>: Zero trust security is crucial in edge computing due to its distributed and dynamic nature. Traditional security models are insufficient for the expanded attack surface in edge environments. Zero trust assumes no inherent trust in any device or entity, requiring continuous identity verification and adherence to security policies. This approach ensures data protection, limits unauthorized access, and adapts to changing conditions. It also aids compliance with data privacy regulations by verifying access rights and encrypting data at the source. Zero trust security is essential for organizations embracing edge computing\'s transformative potential, providing data protection, secure access control, and regulatory compliance in this evolving landscape.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Any-Scale Scalability</strong>: Any-scale scalability is a crucial aspect of edge computing that addresses the dynamic and diverse nature of edge environments. In edge computing, where devices come in various sizes and possess different capabilities, any-scale scalability ensures optimal performance and efficient resource utilization. It enables the seamless integration of new devices while supporting real-time analytics and autonomous systems.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By providing the ability to add or remove devices without disruptions, any-scale scalability allows edge systems to adapt to changing requirements and workloads. It optimizes the allocation of resources, such as processing power and storage, ensuring that tasks are efficiently distributed and executed. This scalability plays a vital role in enhancing the overall performance and responsiveness of edge applications.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One of the high benefits of any-scale scalability is its ability to future-proof edge infrastructure. As emerging technologies continue to evolve, organizations can easily incorporate these advancements into their edge computing systems without major changes to the underlying infrastructure. This flexibility enables businesses to stay at the forefront of innovation in edge computing and take advantage of new opportunities as they arise.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Furthermore, any-scale scalability contributes to improved operational efficiency and costeffectiveness. With the ability to scale resources based on demand, organizations can avoid overprovisioning and unnecessary expenses. They can dynamically adjust resources to match the workload, ensuring optimal resource utilization and reducing operational costs.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In conclusion, any-scale scalability in edge provides the flexibility and adaptability required to meet the dynamic demands of edge environments. It enables seamless device integration, supports real-time analytics, optimizes resource allocation, future-proofs infrastructure, and improves operational efficiency, making it a highly beneficial capability in the world of edge<br>computing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Zero Touch IT</strong>: The requirement for Zero-touch IT in edge computing originates from the unique challenges associated with managing a distributed network of edge devices. Manual configuration and maintenance become impractical due to remote locations and device mobility. Zero-touch IT automates device provisioning, configuration, and management to streamline operations. It reduces deployment time, minimizes errors, and enables scalability. New devices seamlessly integrate into existing infrastructure, and consistent security policies and updates are enforced effortlessly. Zero-touch IT ensures efficient device management, enhanced security, and scalability in edge computing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>[ Human-> Semi Automated –> Fully Automated] Decision Making</strong>: For a long time, human decision-making has been predominant across various industries, relying on professionals to manually analyze data and make informed choices. While this approach benefits from human intuition and expertise, it often encounters challenges related to latency, especially in timesensitive situations. In response, semi-automated decision-making has emerged as a middle ground, combining human knowledge with machine-driven data analysis. This hybrid approach reduces decision latency as algorithms assist human operators in processing and interpreting data.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, the ultimate goal of edge computing is fully automated decision-making. Through the<br>utilization of artificial intelligence and machine learning algorithms, edge devices are capable of processing vast volumes of real-time data and making instantaneous decisions without the<br>need for human intervention. This transformative shift empowers ultra-low latency ecisionmaking, which is crucial for time-critical applications such as autonomous vehicles and industrial automation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By leveraging edge\'s distributed architecture, processing power is brought closer to the data source, enabling real-time decision-making at the edge. This eliminates the need for data to traverse long distances to reach a centralized processing center, thereby significantly reducing latency. With edge devices equipped with advanced algorithms, they can rapidly analyze incoming data, detect patterns, and autonomously make decisions based on predefined rules or learned behaviors.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Fully automated decision-making in edge computing opens up new possibilities for optimizing processes, enhancing efficiency, and ensuring real-time responsiveness in critical applications. It enables industries to operate with unprecedented speed and accuracy, paving the way for advancements in autonomous systems, remote monitoring, predictive maintenance, and more.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In conclusion, while human decision-making and semi-automated approaches have their merits, the ultimate objective of edge computing is to achieve fully automated decision-making. By harnessing the power of artificial intelligence and machine learning at the edge, organizations can attain ultra-low latency decision-making capabilities, revolutionizing industries that rely on real-time, time-critical operations.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Rugged Hardware &amp; Applications</strong>: Rugged hardware and applications are essential in edge computing to withstand harsh environments and ensure optimal performance. Rugged hardware endures extreme conditions like temperature, humidity, vibrations, and shocks, reducing downtime and maintenance costs. Rugged applications are designed to work in resource-constrained and volatile environments, operating efficiently offline or with intermittent connectivity. They enable edge devices to process data and make critical decisions locally. The use of rugged solutions is crucial in industries like manufacturing, energy, transportation, agriculture, and disaster response, where reliable performance in challenging conditions is necessary. Rugged hardware and applications ensure the continuity and resilience of edge computing operations in diverse real-world scenarios.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Challenges</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While edge computing offers significant advantages, its implementation presents several challenges that need to be addressed:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":712,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/EdgeComputing-challenge.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-712\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Heterogeneous Infrastructure: The presence of a heterogeneous infrastructure is a significant challenge in edge computing. Deployments involve a diverse range of devices, sensors, and systems from different vendors with varying specifications, leading to compatibility and interoperability issues. Managing this diversity becomes complex, making it difficult to implement consistent management, security, and monitoring practices. The lack of standardized protocols and interfaces hampers seamless data exchange, resulting in data silos and inefficiencies. Furthermore, varying levels of device performance and reliability can affect overall system stability and data processing consistency. Additionally, the heterogeneity of the infrastructure poses challenges in terms of scalability and upgradability, requiring extensive effort and customization to integrate new devices or technologies, potentially disrupting ongoing operations.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Resource Constraints: Resource constraints in edge computing refer to limitations in computing power, memory, storage, and energy on edge devices. This poses challenges for data processing, analytics, and storage at the edge, especially for real-time and data-intensive tasks.<br>Energy efficiency is crucial for remote or mobile edge devices. Strategies like offloading tasks to centralized servers, utilizing edge-native data processing, and adopting resource-efficient platforms help mitigate constraints. Careful data management, compression, and filtering optimize storage. Overcoming resource constraints enables organizations to leverage the full potential of edge computing, delivering real-time, context-aware, and intelligent services across various applications and industries. Innovative solutions and thoughtful consideration of resources empower the success of edge devices and systems.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Data Management: Data management in edge computing faces challenges due to distributed<br>deployments and diverse devices. Data security and privacy are critical, requiring encryption and access controls. Low latency for real-time processing is essential, necessitating efficient algorithms and caching. Data interoperability is a challenge due to varying formats and protocols, requiring standardization and normalization. Storage constraints demand careful data selection for availability and resource optimization. Data governance and compliance must navigate regional regulations while ensuring quality. Overall, effective data management in edge computing requires robust security measures, low-latency processing, interoperability solutions, smart storage strategies, and adherence to data governance and compliance standards.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Security Risks: Security risks in edge computing are a significant concern due to the distributed and diverse nature of edge devices and systems. Challenges include an increased attack surface, limited resources for implementing robust security measures, physical vulnerabilities in remote environments, a lack of standardization in security protocols, and trade-offs between latency and security. Connectivity and offline risks, as well as remote management complexities, further compound the security landscape. Addressing these challenges requires a comprehensive approach, including tailored security technologies, robust policies, regular updates, edge-native security solutions, and promoting security awareness among the workforces. Organizations must adapt security measures to the unique requirements of edge devices while fostering a security-conscious culture to effectively mitigate risks in the dynamic world of edge computing security.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Performance &amp; Cost Optimization: Performance and cost optimization in edge computing present challenges due to device diversity, network limitations, device management, and workload distribution. Heterogeneous devices with varying capabilities require careful resource management and algorithm selection. Limited connectivity in remote environments necessitates advanced networking solutions. Managing numerous dispersed devices efficiently is crucial for cost optimization. Striking the right balance between edge and centralized processing ensures optimal performance and cost efficiency. Analyzing data requirements and usage patterns helps determine the ideal workload distribution. Organizations must consider these factors to achieve efficient and sustainable edge deployments, delivering real-time processing, reduced latency, and cost-effective operations.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Lack Of Technical Resources: The rapid adoption of edge computing has led to a shortage of technical professionals skilled in designing, implementing, and managing edge computing solutions. The demand for expertise in networking, cybersecurity, data analytics, hardware engineering, and cloud computing poses a challenge due to the unique requirements of edge computing. Specialists capable of working in resource-constrained environments and handling distributed systems are particularly scarce. Furthermore, the lack of standardized training and certifications for edge computing hampers the development of a skilled workforce. While efforts are underway to address this gap, there is still a significant need for skilled professionals to meet the growing demand for edge computing expertise.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Lack Of purpose-built technology: The evolving nature of edge computing presents challenges due to the lack of purpose-built technology designed specifically for edge deployments. Off-theshelf solutions often fall short in meeting the unique requirements of resource-constrained environments, leading to suboptimal performance, increased costs, and management complexities. Compatibility issues arise from the diverse range of edge devices and systems.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Additionally, the absence of purpose-built solutions for remote or harsh environments can result in frequent failures and increased maintenance costs. Specialized security measures are essential to protect data and ensure the integrity of the edge infrastructure. Addressing these challenges requires the development and adoption of purpose-built hardware, software, and security solutions tailored to the specific needs of edge computing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Approaches for Overcoming Challenges</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To address the challenges inherent in edge computing, following methods can be implemented for effective solutions</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":713,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/EdgeComputing-approach.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-713\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Standardization and Interoperability</strong> Standardization and interoperability are crucial for successful edge computing. Strategies to address these challenges include industry collaboration, adopting open standards, data and service abstraction, testing and certification, and continuous monitoring and improvement. Collaboration among stakeholders helps establish common frameworks and protocols. Embracing open standards prevents vendor lockin. Standardizing data formats, APIs, and service interfaces facilitates seamless data exchange. Testing and certification processes ensure compliance and interoperability. Continuous monitoring allows for updates and improvements. These efforts foster interoperability, enabling seamless integration and collaboration between edge devices, systems, and applications.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Edge Data Caching and Prioritization</strong>: Data caching and prioritization play a vital role in optimizing data processing, reducing latency, and improving system performance in edge computing. Strategies to address these challenges include content-based caching, where data is cached based on its characteristics, proactive caching that predicts and pre-fetches data, dynamic caching and eviction that adjust cache content based on real-time demand, data prioritization to allocate resources efficiently, and machine learning-based techniques to analyze data patterns and optimize caching decisions. These methods ensure that frequently accessed and critical data is readily available at the edge devices, reducing latency, improving responsiveness, and enhancing the overall efficiency of edge computing systems.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Secure Bootstrapping and Over-the-Air Updates</strong>: Secure bootstrapping and over-the-air (OTA) updates are essential for the security, reliability, and scalability of edge computing. Secure bootstrapping involves device identity and authentication, secure communication, and a zero-trust model to ensure trusted connections and authorized access. OTA updates require code signing and verification, incremental updates to minimize bandwidth usage, rollback mechanisms for resilience, and strict update policies for controlled deployment. These methods safeguard edge devices from unauthorized access, ensure the integrity of firmware updates, and enable efficient and secure software maintenance. By implementing robust secure bootstrapping and OTA update mechanisms, organizations can maintain a secure and up-todate edge infrastructure, protect against vulnerabilities, and ensure the continuous operation and trustworthiness of edge devices and systems.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>TinyML</strong>: TinyML is a revolutionary paradigm that enables machine learning to run on embedded edge devices with limited processing power and memory. These devices typically operate within strict power consumption constraints, aiming for a few milliwatts or less. TinyML leverages sophisticated power management modules and hardware acceleration to facilitate IoT-based embedded edge devices to operate on lower power systems. The software used in TinyML scenarios is designed to be as compact as possible, ensuring efficient power usage.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One of the key objectives of TinyML is to optimize machine learning models to deliver accurate results while operating under resource-constrained environments. TinyML systems must meet specific requirements, including support for energy-harvesting edge devices, battery-operated embedded edge devices, scalability to accommodate a vast number of affordable embedded devices, and the ability to store codes within a few kilobytes in on-device RAM.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Currently, machine learning devices are primarily hosted in public or private cloud infrastructures. Organizations rely on cloud-based machine learning services for industrial applications, but this dependence poses challenges such as high energy consumption, privacy concerns, network and processing latency, and reliability issues. TinyML recognizes that the physical world itself holds valuable intelligence. By enabling decision-making at the embedded edge devices before relying on edge AI or cloud AI, TinyML offers several improvements, including enhanced energy efficiency, improved privacy for local data, reduced processing latency, and minimized dependency on connectivity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In conclusion, TinyML is a game-changer in the field of machine learning, allowing it to operate on resource-constrained embedded edge devices. By harnessing the power of the physical world and enabling decision-making at the edge, TinyML systems offer significant advantages such as energy efficiency, data privacy &amp; low latency.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Abstraction Layer &amp; Micro Controllers</strong>: The utilization of an abstraction layer above the kernel layer and microcontrollers plays a vital role in the creation of efficient edge computing solutions. This abstraction layer acts as a bridge between the application software and hardware, simplifying their interaction and promoting portability and interoperability. It relieves developers from the complexities of low-level hardware intricacies, allowing them to focus more on application development.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Microcontrollers, on the other hand, serve as compact and efficient computing units for edge devices. They enable local processing, data collection, and real-time decision-making, significantly reducing latency and enhancing responsiveness. When combined with the abstraction layer, microcontrollers contribute to hardware independence, application portability, and flexibility in edge computing deployments.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The synergy between the abstraction layer and microcontrollers facilitates seamless integration of diverse services and components in edge computing. It promotes modularity, enabling organizations to easily incorporate different edge devices and architectures into their solutions. This flexibility empowers organizations to optimize their edge computing deployments and adapt to evolving requirements.<br>By leveraging the benefits of the abstraction layer and microcontrollers, organizations can streamline the development and management of edge applications. This streamlining improves scalability and enhances the overall effectiveness of edge computing solutions. It allows for efficient resource utilization, faster deployment cycles, and simplified maintenance, ultimately leading to more robust and efficient edge computing ecosystems.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In conclusion, the abstraction layer and microcontrollers are crucial components in creating effective edge computing solutions. They provide hardware independence, promote application portability, and facilitate flexibility in deployments. By leveraging these elements, organizations can unlock the full potential of edge computing, driving innovation and maximizing the benefits of this distributed computing paradigm.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Containerization of Hardware</strong>: The containerization of hardware in edge computing is highly significant for efficient, scalable, and flexible deployment of applications and services at the edge. Containerization enables resource efficiency by utilizing hardware effectively, allowing multiple applications to run concurrently on the same edge device without conflicts. It provides application portability, simplifying deployment and migration across different edge devices. Container orchestration platforms simplify management, enhance security through isolation, and enable agility by facilitating rapid deployment and updates. Containerization in edge computing offers flexibility, scalability, and streamlined operations, enabling organizations to maximize the potential of their edge deployments and deliver applications efficiently and reliably.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Conclusion</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":714,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/EdgeComputing-securitystratum-1024x428.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-714\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Edge computing is an innovative paradigm that has the power to revolutionize industries through the utilization of distributed intelligence. While all the components of edge computing are significant, certain factors hold the key. TinyML represents a breakthrough in running machine learning on resource-constrained embedded edge devices. Its integration allows for local processing and real-time decision-making, enhancing responsiveness and reducing latency. The sophistication of the abstraction layer above highly optimized microcontrollers simplifies the interaction between application software and hardware, promoting portability and interoperability. It empowers developers to focus on application development rather than getting lost in low-level hardware intricacies.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In addition, any-scale scalability ensures that edge computing infrastructure can dynamically adapt to changing workloads and accommodate a diverse range of devices and applications. This scalability capability allows for efficient resource allocation and provisioning, optimizing the performance of edge applications.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Present implementations of generative AI, particularly involving Large Language Models (LLM), fall short of taking a prominent role in Edge computing due to their inability to reliably discern truth from falsehood. Furthermore, their effectiveness is contingent upon the quality of the dataset and lacks inherent intelligence.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By combining TinyML, an efficient abstraction layer, and any-scale scalability, edge computing can truly unleash its transformative potential. It enables automated decision-making, enhances responsiveness, promotes application portability, and allows for seamless resource scaling. This convergence of technologies and capabilities has the capacity to revolutionize industries and drive innovation in the era of distributed intelligence.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','The Transformative Potential of Edge Computing','','draft','open','closed','','','','','2025-01-05 19:38:13','2025-01-05 19:38:13','',0,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/?post_type=market_research&#038;p=709',0,'market_research','',0),(710,14,'2025-01-05 19:02:35','2025-01-05 19:02:35','','goalofEdgeComputing','','inherit','open','closed','','goalofedgecomputing','','','2025-01-05 19:02:35','2025-01-05 19:02:35','',709,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/goalofEdgeComputing.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(711,14,'2025-01-05 19:06:22','2025-01-05 19:06:22','','EdgeComputing-essential','','inherit','open','closed','','edgecomputing-essential','','','2025-01-05 19:06:22','2025-01-05 19:06:22','',709,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/EdgeComputing-essential.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(712,14,'2025-01-05 19:16:51','2025-01-05 19:16:51','','EdgeComputing-challenge','','inherit','open','closed','','edgecomputing-challenge','','','2025-01-05 19:16:51','2025-01-05 19:16:51','',709,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/EdgeComputing-challenge.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(713,14,'2025-01-05 19:23:09','2025-01-05 19:23:09','','EdgeComputing-approach','','inherit','open','closed','','edgecomputing-approach','','','2025-01-05 19:23:09','2025-01-05 19:23:09','',709,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/EdgeComputing-approach.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(714,14,'2025-01-05 19:36:34','2025-01-05 19:36:34','','EdgeComputing-securitystratum','','inherit','open','closed','','edgecomputing-securitystratum','','','2025-01-05 19:36:34','2025-01-05 19:36:34','',709,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/EdgeComputing-securitystratum.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(715,14,'2025-01-05 19:38:43','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','open','closed','','','','','2025-01-05 19:38:43','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/?post_type=market_research&p=715',0,'market_research','',0),(716,14,'2025-01-06 02:28:36','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Executive Summary</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Containers, while promoting innovation, also introduce new security risks. To ensure container security, a comprehensive approach is necessary, combining people, processes, and technology. Investments in training and solutions provide long-term benefits, and proper diligence throughout the container lifecycle is essential.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Primary goal is to address security concerns related to container technologies and offer practical recommendations for managing these concerns at all stages of container usage, from planning to maintenance.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>This playbook establishes criteria for evaluating container security solutions, providing a comprehensive perspective on the subject. Adhering to these criteria would enable IT leaders and architects to effectively address the complexities of container security, ultimately fostering a safer and more efficient containerized environment.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Leading container security solutions, including Red Hat Advanced Cluster Security, Palo Alto Prisma Cloud, Aqua Security, NeuVector, Anchore, Sysdig Secure, Qualys, and Snyk, are evaluated based on comprehensive criteria.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Cultivating a culture of security and vigilance within container workflows is vital.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Introduction</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The integration of container technologies has profoundly disrupted the established culture and software development methodologies within the organization. With the advent of containers, traditional approaches to development, patching, and system upgrades may no longer be directly applicable, necessitating a willingness among employees to embrace a new model. To ensure a successful transition, it is crucial for the staff to be open to adapting their practices and methodologies.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this guide, we will cover recommended practices for securely building and operating applications within containers, offering essential insights for employees to follow. It is of utmost importance for the organization to reevaluate existing procedures to fully capitalize on the benefits that containers can bring.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The primary objective of this document is to shed light on the security concerns associated with container technologies and provide practical recommendations for effectively addressing these concerns throughout the planning, implementation, and maintenance stages of container usage. By heeding these guidelines, the organization can navigate the challenges and intricacies of container security, fostering a safer and more efficient containerized environment.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Overall, embracing containerization and its accompanying best practices will enable the organization to propel its software development processes to new heights while safeguarding against potential security vulnerabilities.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Scope</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Container security has a vast scope, covering a diverse set of practices, tools,<br>and strategies that work together to safeguard every aspect of the containerized application lifecycle. From the initial stages of development to the final deployment, container security ensures comprehensive protection.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This includes safeguarding the container images themselves, as well as the runtime environments in which they operate. It also extends to the container orchestration platforms that manage and coordinate containerized applications, ensuring their security and integrity. Moreover, container security encompasses the protection of the underlying infrastructure, which forms the foundation for containerization. By delving deeper into the specific aspects of container security, one can gain a thorough understanding of the measures and techniques employed to maintain the safety and reliability of containerized applications throughout their lifecycle. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":717,\"width\":\"840px\",\"height\":\"auto\",\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-resized\"><img src=\"https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/ContainerSecurity-scope.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-717\" style=\"width:840px;height:auto\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Image Security</strong>: Ensuring the security of container images is essential. This involves using only trusted base images, regularly updating images, and scanning for vulnerabilities in the images and their dependencies. Implementing secure image repositories and using digital signatures can also enhance image security.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Vulnerability Management</strong>: Identifying and mitigating vulnerabilities in the software components used within containers is a critical aspect of container security. Regularly scanning and patching container images, as well as monitoring for new vulnerabilities, are essential practices.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Access Control</strong>: Proper access controls must be enforced to limit container access to authorized users and processes. Implementing rolebased access control (RBAC) and employing least privilege principles help reduce the attack surface. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Network Security</strong>: Containers communicate over networks, and securing these interactions is crucial. Employing network policies, firewalls, and service mesh helps prevent unauthorized access and potential lateral movement within the infrastructure. Firewall adds more value when placed at the edge of the cluster. If performance is the most important factor, then the firewall can be placed inside the containers themselves. With popular service mesh implementations like Istio and Linkerd, one can use tools and configuration resources to inject sidecar proxies alongside application containers and define policies within the Kubernetes environment. </li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Runtime Security</strong>: Monitoring container behavior during runtime is vital to detect and respond to security threats in real-time. Runtime security tools can detect unusual activities, unauthorized access<br>attempts, and potential indicators of compromise.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Secrets Management</strong>: Managing sensitive data such as passwords, API keys, and other credentials securely is a fundamental part of container security. Using encryption and secure storage solutions, as well as limiting access to secrets, helps protect critical information.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Orchestration Platform Security</strong>: Container orchestration platforms like Kubernetes play a central role in managing containers. Securing the orchestration platform itself is essential to prevent attacks on the control plane and unauthorized access to sensitive information.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Compliance and Auditing</strong>: Container security should align with relevant security standards and regulatory requirements. Regular auditing and compliance checks ensure that security practices are<br>maintained and followed.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>CI/CD Pipeline Security</strong>: Integrating security into the CI/CD pipeline helps identify and address vulnerabilities early in the development process. Secure development practices, code analysis, and continuous security testing are crucial components.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Incident Response and Forensics</strong>: Having a well-defined incident response plan specific to container-related incidents is vital. This includes procedures for containing threats, investigating breaches,<br>and restoring services.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Continuous Monitoring and Threat Detection</strong>: Implementing continuous monitoring and threat detection mechanisms allows for proactive identification of potential security risks and anomalies.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Container Isolation</strong>: Ensuring proper isolation between containers and host systems prevents container escape and protects the underlying infrastructure.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Risks</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Containers provide immense benefits like portable workloads, resource efficiency, and scalability. However, as with any technology, they also introduce new security risks that must be managed. While not exhaustive, some key risks include:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":718,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/ContainerSecurity-risks.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-718\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Container breakout</strong>: This involves an attacker breaking out of the container and accessing the underlying host infrastructure. It can happen if the container runtime is vulnerable or misconfigured in a way that allows escaping namespaces, capabilities, cgroups, etc.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Privilege escalation</strong>: Containers often run as root or have more privileges than required. This allows an attacker who compromises a container to gain elevated privileges on the host. Privileges should be limited via pod security contexts, read-only filesystems, etc.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Resource exhaustion</strong>: Containers can be used to launch denial of service attacks by consuming excessive compute, memory, storage, or network resources on the host. Resource limits should be set on containers.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Image vulnerabilities:</strong> Images may contain software with known vulnerabilities, insecure default configurations, or malicious injections. Images should be scanned, signed, and obtained from trusted sources only.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Insecure APIs</strong>: Application and Orchestration platform APIs should be secured with auth, encryption, auditing. API endpoints exposed on containers also need proper protection.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Network attacks</strong>: Pods can access each other over the network by default in Kubernetes. Network policies should restrict communication to prevent reconnaissance, lateral movement, etc.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Inadequate isolation:</strong> Shared compute, storage, network resources can allow inter-container attacks and data leaks. Use security contexts, namespaces, filesystem policies to isolate as needed.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Platform vulnerabilities:</strong> Flaws in the container runtime, OS distro, Kubernetes platform can compromise security controls and container isolation. Timely patching and hardening is important.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Insecure configurations:</strong> Misconfigurations of RBAC policies, admission controls, auditing, secrets management, etc. can undermine Kubernetes security. Follow principle of least privilege.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Compromised registries:</strong> Container registries can be hacked to distribute backdoored or malicious images intended for Kubernetes deployments. Sign, scan and verify images.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Product Evaluation Criteria</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When evaluating container security software, there are several key metrics to consider. Based on the research I have identified the following fundamental parameters that serve as the basis for evaluating container security products. These metrics play a crucial role in determining the effectiveness and<br>reliability of container security solutions. By considering these parameters, businesses can make informed decisions and select the most suitable container security software for their needs.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":719,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/ContainerSecurity-criteria.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-719\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Data Protection – Does the solution protect the data that is stored in containers, both at rest and in transit? Does it include encrypting data, controlling access to data, and detecting and responding to data breaches.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Network Security – To what extent does the solution safeguard the container network? This entails the use of firewalls, intrusion detection systems, and encryption to thwart unauthorized access to containers and their data.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Vulnerability management – Does the solution possess the capability to scan container images and running containers for vulnerabilities in the operating system, libraries, dependencies, and application code? This is crucial for ensuring the security of container images.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Performance &amp; Scalability - How effectively does the solution scale with the growth of your cluster? Are there limitations on the number of nodes it can manage? Does scaling impact performance?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Compliance – To what degree does the solution assist organizations in achieving compliance with pertinent regulations such as the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) and the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS)?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Runtime protection – Does the solution offer real-time defenses against threats like malware, unauthorized access, anomaly detection, and compliance monitoring for actively running containers?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Incident monitoring &amp; response – Does the solution provide monitoring for container activities, alerting for potential threats, investigative capabilities for swift incident response, and support for<br>forensic analysis?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Cost-effectiveness - How cost effective is the solution compared to similar alternatives? Is pricing per-node or flat annually? Does it impose unnecessary costs?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Ecosystem integration - How seamlessly does the solution integrate with the container ecosystem, including Kubernetes, CI/CD tools, the host operating system, and public cloud platforms?</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Product Review<br></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><em><strong>Red Hat Advanced Cluster Security for Kubernetes®</strong></em></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Key Takeaways</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Kubernetes-native architecture leverages Kube’s declarative data and built-in controls for richer context, native enforcement, and continuous hardening</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Leverages the controls built into Kubernetes for policy enforcement, avoiding the operational risks of applying third-party in-line proxying or blocking tools.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Applies intelligence from runtime behavior to adjust subsequent builds and deployments to continuously monitor and shrink the attack surface.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Reduces the time and effort needed to implement security and streamlines security analysis, investigation, and remediation using the rich context Kubernetes provides.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Provides scalability and resiliency native to Kubernetes, avoiding operational conflict and complexity that can result from out-of-band security controls.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":720,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/ContainerSecurity-redhat.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-720\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><em><strong>Palo Alto Prisma Cloud®</strong></em></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Key Takeaways</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Scans container images and enforces policies as part of CI/CD workflows.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Continuously monitors code in repositories and registries.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Secures both managed and unmanaged runtime environments.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Combines risk prioritization with runtime protection at scale.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Support for public and private clouds</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Single console for managed and unmanaged environments</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Full life cycle security for repositories, images, and containers</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Aggregates and prioritizes vulnerabilities continuously in CI/CD pipelines and containers running on hosts or on containers as a service.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":721,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/ContainerSecurity-PaloAlto-1024x672.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-721\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><em>Aqua Security®</em></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><br><strong>Key Takeaways</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Kubernetes Security Posture Management (KSPM) and Kubernetes runtime protection provide policy-driven life cycle protection and compliance for K8s applications.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Dynamic map of running K8s clusters that highlights and rates Kubernetes security risks.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Real-time visibility into namespaces, deployments, nodes (hosts), containers and the images they came from, as well as network connections between and within namespaces.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Powered by Open Policy Agent (OPA), new Kubernetes Assurance Policies apply dozens of rules or add custom rules using Rego expressions.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Works in conjunction with Aqua’s Image Assurance Policies to prevent the deployment of unsafe and non-compliant workloads.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Discover malware hidden in open-source packages and third-party images, preventing attacks on container-based applications.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Analyzes images before they arrive in a secure isolated sandboxed environment, examining and tracing behavioral anomalies</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Static and dynamic scanning to create flexible image assurance policies that determine which images would be allowed to progress through the development pipeline and run in clusters or hosts.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":722,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/ContainerSecurity-Aqua.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-722\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><em>Neuvector</em>®</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><br><strong>Key Takeaways</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>NeuVector can be deployed through the Rancher catalog.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Pushes security capabilities across the entire cloud-native footprint.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Ensures container security using network inspection.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>NeuVector will be available as an add-on to SUSE Rancher</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Supports the full range of Kubernetes management products in addition to Rancher and including OpenShift, Mirantis, and Tanzu.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Scans for vulnerabilities during the entire CI/CD pipeline</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Uses the Jenkins plug-in to scan during build, monitor images in registries, and run automated tests for security compliance.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Prevents deployment of vulnerable images with admission control, and monitor production containers.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Deploys as a container onto virtual machines or bare metal OS environments.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Scanning and admission control during build, test, and deployment</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Layer 7 container firewall.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":723,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/image.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-723\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><em>Anchore</em>®</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Key Takeaways</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Software supply chain management built with the software bill of materials (SBOM) to identify upstream dependencies in source code repositories and monitor for SBOM drift that can indicate malware or compromised software.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Automatically generate SBOMs for all software produced and verify SBOMs for software consumed (both open source and proprietary)</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Use SBOM data to continuously assess security and compliance risks before and after deployment.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Continuously monitor software applications for new or zero-day vulnerabilities that arise.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Extends scanning for dependencies to include source code repositories in addition to support for container scanning through CI/CD, registries, or Kubernetes.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Container registries include Harbor, Quay, JFrog, and DockerHub as well as offerings from AWS, Azure, and Google</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Reports and evaluations can be accessed using the command-line interface (CLI) or Anchore Enterprise UI, and webhooks can trigger action in other systems.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Open-source tools for image inspection and vulnerability scanning perform analysis of container workloads.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Ensures no secrets are present in images such as passwords and API keys.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Identifies non-OS third-party libraries, including Node.js NPM, Ruby GEM, Python PIP, DotNet, and Java archives.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":724,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/image-1.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-724\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong><em>Sysdig Secure®</em></strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Key Takeaways</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>A new Drift Control feature helps teams to detect, prevent, and speed up incident response for containers that were modified in production, also known as container drift.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Malware and crypto mining detection with threat intelligence feeds from Proofpoint Emerging Threats (ET) Intelligence and the Sysdig Threat Research Team</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Digs directly into compromised or suspicious containers with ondemand secured shell access and investigates the blocked executable and communications.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Automates scanning locally in continuous integration and continuous deployment (CI/CD) pipelines and registries without images leaving the environment.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Visualizes network communication between pods, services, and applications inside Kubernetes.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Conducts incident response using granular data with Kubernetes and cloud context and forwards events to SIEM tools like Splunk, QRadar, AWS Security Hub</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Continuously validates cloud security posture and meets compliance standards (e.g., NIST 800-53, SOC2, and PCI) and internal mandates.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":725,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/image-2.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-725\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Qualys®</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Key Takeaways</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Secures containers whether on-premises and in the cloud.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Enforce policies to block the use of images that have specific vulnerabilities or that have vulnerabilities above a certain severity threshold.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Vulnerability detection and remediation in the DevOps pipeline by deploying plugins like Jenkins or Bamboo or via REST APIs</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Search for images that have high-severity vulnerabilities, unapproved packages, and older or test release tags.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Container Runtime Security (CRS) offers visibility into running containers as well as the ability to enforce policies that govern behavior.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Centralized discovery and tracking for containers and images.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>View metadata for containers and images including labels, tags, installed software, and layers.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Coverage of Linux OS distributions to container-centric OSs, applications, and programming languages</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":726,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img src=\"https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/image-3.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-726\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->','Playbook For Adopting Container Security Solutions','','draft','open','closed','','','','','2025-01-06 02:28:36','2025-01-06 02:28:36','',0,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/?post_type=market_research&#038;p=716',0,'market_research','',0),(717,14,'2025-01-05 20:04:03','2025-01-05 20:04:03','','ContainerSecurity-scope','','inherit','open','closed','','containersecurity-scope','','','2025-01-05 20:04:03','2025-01-05 20:04:03','',716,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/ContainerSecurity-scope.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(718,14,'2025-01-05 20:09:43','2025-01-05 20:09:43','','ContainerSecurity-risks','','inherit','open','closed','','containersecurity-risks','','','2025-01-05 20:09:43','2025-01-05 20:09:43','',716,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/ContainerSecurity-risks.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(719,14,'2025-01-05 20:56:39','2025-01-05 20:56:39','','ContainerSecurity-criteria','','inherit','open','closed','','containersecurity-criteria','','','2025-01-05 20:56:39','2025-01-05 20:56:39','',716,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/ContainerSecurity-criteria.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(720,14,'2025-01-05 21:01:56','2025-01-05 21:01:56','','ContainerSecurity-redhat','','inherit','open','closed','','containersecurity-redhat','','','2025-01-05 21:01:56','2025-01-05 21:01:56','',716,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/ContainerSecurity-redhat.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(721,14,'2025-01-05 21:04:56','2025-01-05 21:04:56','','ContainerSecurity-PaloAlto','','inherit','open','closed','','containersecurity-paloalto','','','2025-01-05 21:04:56','2025-01-05 21:04:56','',716,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/ContainerSecurity-PaloAlto.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(722,14,'2025-01-05 22:28:18','2025-01-05 22:28:18','','ContainerSecurity-Aqua','','inherit','open','closed','','containersecurity-aqua','','','2025-01-05 22:28:18','2025-01-05 22:28:18','',716,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/ContainerSecurity-Aqua.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(723,14,'2025-01-05 22:30:43','2025-01-05 22:30:43','','image','','inherit','open','closed','','image-2','','','2025-01-05 22:30:43','2025-01-05 22:30:43','',716,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/image.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(724,14,'2025-01-05 22:33:36','2025-01-05 22:33:36','','image','','inherit','open','closed','','image-3','','','2025-01-05 22:33:36','2025-01-05 22:33:36','',716,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/image-1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(725,14,'2025-01-05 22:36:24','2025-01-05 22:36:24','','image','','inherit','open','closed','','image-4','','','2025-01-05 22:36:24','2025-01-05 22:36:24','',716,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/image-2.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(726,14,'2025-01-05 22:38:42','2025-01-05 22:38:42','','image','','inherit','open','closed','','image-5','','','2025-01-05 22:38:42','2025-01-05 22:38:42','',716,'https://tech24.wpenginepowered.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/image-3.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0);
